    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "9de920fd_91417c85",
        "filename": "android/skin/qt/event-capture.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 89,
      "author": {
        "id": 1079748
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-10T22:22:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Why?\n\nWhat use case do you forsee that justifies this complexity?\n\nThe subscribers could simply be required to call |unsubscribe| to stop receiving events. In addition, this solves the problem of the subscribe being able to test if EventCapturer is gone away (by checking that the token is valid). Do you see that use case somewhere?",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 87,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 89,
        "endChar": 60
      },
      "revId": "250f315fe7cac92d64ca9b3de8c51b6645c51ca1",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fde3fc1c_95f5e636",
        "filename": "android/skin/qt/event-capture.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 89,
      "author": {
        "id": 1078773
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-11T05:29:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "1) This simplifies the subscriber\u0027s job. Instead of worrying about calling unsub, all it has to do is hold on to the token. It will unsubscribe automatically when the subscriber is destroyed.  It\u0027s managing subscriptions using the RAII idiom.\n\n2) Also, this hides EventCapture\u0027s implementation details from the subscribers (avoids exposing the iterator to the internal list)\n\nSee UIEventRecorder for an example of how this works.",
      "parentUuid": "9de920fd_91417c85",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 87,
        "startChar": 0,
        "endLine": 89,
        "endChar": 60
      },
      "revId": "250f315fe7cac92d64ca9b3de8c51b6645c51ca1",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fde3fc1c_0c4e97b0",
        "filename": "android/skin/qt/event-capture.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 1079748
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-10T22:22:28Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I have a slight preference to an enum class for the top level windows here instead of an object.\n\nThat way, subscribers are insulated from having to search for the top level window objects.\n\nIt does mean that you can\u0027t subscribe to a lower level QObject than a top level window. I would like that defintion of  EventCapturer, I think.",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 12,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "250f315fe7cac92d64ca9b3de8c51b6645c51ca1",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "fde3fc1c_75227a8c",
        "filename": "android/skin/qt/event-capture.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 1078773
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-11T05:29:18Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Unfortunately, top-level windows can pop in and out of existence (i.e. a new instance of ExtendedWindow is constructed every time it\u0027s shown, and it\u0027s destroyed when it\u0027s closed). This makes your proposed method problematic. A possible solution is to emit a signal when certain top-level windows are created, and tie that signal to subscribers\u0027 slot.",
      "parentUuid": "fde3fc1c_0c4e97b0",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 12,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "250f315fe7cac92d64ca9b3de8c51b6645c51ca1",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "3ddaf464_97bccee2",
        "filename": "android/skin/qt/event-capture.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 1079748
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-11T17:59:23Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "That actually is an example for why I would like enums here.\n\nIn the current implementation, subscribers have to themselves keep track of when the windows are created / destroyed), and resubscribe (with a new token each time?)\n\nIn my proposal, the subscriber just conveys its intention that it wants to hear from the WindowType::ExtendedWindow. Then, it is this objects responsibility to track that window\u0027s lifecycle and re-register as needed.",
      "parentUuid": "fde3fc1c_75227a8c",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 12,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "250f315fe7cac92d64ca9b3de8c51b6645c51ca1",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "7d09ccae_226de2cf",
        "filename": "android/skin/qt/event-capture.h",
        "patchSetId": 3
      },
      "lineNbr": 91,
      "author": {
        "id": 1078773
      },
      "writtenOn": "2016-02-11T20:44:37Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "I don\u0027t think it\u0027s possible to get notified when an instance of a widget gets created. It\u0027s possible to emit a signal when the widget is shown, but there is no way to tie that signal to a slot at a time when the would-be emitter of the signal hasn\u0027t materialized yet. It\u0027s also possible for the *creator* of the widget to emit a signal immediately after creating the said widget, however this isn\u0027t very different from just calling into EventCapturer. If you know of other ways to get notified when an instance of a widget is created, I\u0027d be happy to use them.",
      "parentUuid": "3ddaf464_97bccee2",
      "range": {
        "startLine": 91,
        "startChar": 12,
        "endLine": 91,
        "endChar": 26
      },
      "revId": "250f315fe7cac92d64ca9b3de8c51b6645c51ca1",
      "serverId": "85c56323-6fa9-3386-8a01-6480fb634889",
      "unresolved": false
    },
    {
